@BrucePay You're right, that isn't quite what I wish to do.

I have the following class in a binary module I am making.
```csharp
    [Cmdlet(VerbsDiagnostic.Test, "Widget")]
    public class TestWidgetCommand : PSCmdlet
    {
        protected override void ProcessRecord()
        {
            base.ProcessRecord();
            // I can do this to invoke other cmdlets defined in this binary module.
            var result = (new OtherCmdletFromMyModuleWrittenInCsharp()).Invoke();

            // here I would like to call something like 'Get-Member $result'
        }
    }
```

I hope the comments I have left in the code above help to further clarify my question.

More abstractly, I want to invoke a cmdlet that either exists (in script form instead of C#) as part of my module or external to my module (think system provided cmdlets, like `Get-Member`). If ` public class TestWidgetCommand : PSCmdlet { ... }` were written as `function Restore-Database { ... }`, the answer would be to just call `Get-Member $result` in the body of the function, but I am working in C# and can't do that.

Must I do some thing like this: [Runpool PowerShell Example](https://code.msdn.microsoft.com/PowerShell-Sample-02-affe8453/sourcecode?fileId=70908&pathId=720601728) (see the string script variable)

@cskwrd You do have to use the `PowerShell` API to call other commands from C# but you don't need to create new runspaces. Instead, use `PowerShell.Create(RunspaceMode.CurrentRunspace)` to create the `PowerShell` instance (this is assuming that you don't want to do asynchronous stuff). That way, you'll have access to the current session. So
```csharp
var myPowerShellInstance = PowerShell.Create(RunspaceMode.CurrentRunspace).
    AddCommand("OtherCmdletFromMyModuleWrittenInCsharp");
Collection<PSObject> result = myPowerShellInstance.Invoke();
```
Then to call `Get-Member` with the results,
```csharp 
var mySecondPowerShellInstance = PowerShell.Create(RunspaceMode.CurrentRunspace).
    AddCommand("Get-Member");
Collection<PSObject> result2 = mySecondPowerShellInstance.Invoke(result1);
```
(Note:  WRT getting members, the `Invoke()` method returns `Collection<PSObject>` and  `PSObject` has a property `Members` which is essentially what `Get-Member` returns.)

Or you can do it all in one pipeline
```csharp
 var myPowerShellInstance = PowerShell.Create(RunspaceMode.CurrentRunspace).
    AddCommand("OtherCmdletFromMyModuleWrittenInCsharp").
         AddCommand("Get-Member");
Collection<PSObject> result = myPowerShellInstance.Invoke();
```
And remember to dispose your `PowerShell` instances. Also, you can reuse a `PowerShell` instance by calling `myPowerShellInstance.Commands.Clear()` which removes the commands from the pipeline.
